In Suzanne Collins's The Hunger Games, the powerful Capitol controls all facets of Panem life in its 12 districts; however, the annual Hunger Games represents the harshest power the Capitol possesses over Panem's inhabitants- their survival.
The male and female tributes from each district must risk their lives for sport and entertainment to prove to the Capitol they are totally at their mercy to fight for their lives in a televised game of survival.
To prepare for this physical endurance, the tributes are allotted skill sessions prior to the games and then are given time to impress the gamemakers and certain advisors in the Capitol in order to receive their rankings before the games begin.
During Katniss's individual skills session, she is infatuated with the technology present for her use and finds herself lost in the moment of doing what comes most natural to her- shooting, only to see the gamemakers have moved their attention elsewhere.
Katniss's infatuation with the capitol's weapons and her pride in her shooting contrasted with the gamemakers lack of interest shows the capitol's disrespect for human life; this is important because in order to gain the attention of the Capitol and achieve what she wants Katniss must sacrifice her safety for her survival.
Collins uses weapons as representation of strength and control, and Katniss's exhilaration over the Capitol's state of the art bow and arrow overrides her disapproval of the overall purpose the weapons have- to partake in the training of the Hunger Games.
In the moment, she lets her emotions control her mind much like she did dressing up for the opening ceremonies.
