In the world Beatrice lives in, it is very dangerous to receive divergent results through the aptitude test.
Those who receive divergent results, such as Beatrice, do not predominantly fit the characteristics of a single faction, rather the divergent display characteristics of multiple factions equally.
The Erudite faction, who are traditionally curious for knowledge, are becoming power thirsty.
Their leader developed the simulations which determine the test results which she describes as her "greatest achievement as a scientist (Roth 356)" which leads her to take a special interest in why Beatrice's results were manually recorded.
During the conversation between Beatrice and Jeanine, both try to manipulate the other; Beatrice lied in order to protect her identity at all costs and Jeanine hid her real motives in investigating Beatrice by questioning the aptitude results and her presence on the Erudite compound.
Since the book is written in first person in Beatrice's view, we can see that from one side of this female-female dynamic she can sense she is being lied to.
